(2175, 1, '2015-11-13 08:48:08', '2015-11-13 08:48:08', 'Cinsaut or Cinsault (/ˈsænsoʊ/ san-soh) is a red wine grape, whose heat tolerance and productivity make it important in Languedoc-Roussillon and the former French colonies of Algeria and Morocco. It is often blended with grapes such as Grenache and Carignan to add softness and bouquet.\n In South Africa, Cinsault was once known as Hermitage and was famously crossed with Pinot Noir in 1925 to create Pinotage.\nDubbed the ''Pinot Noir of the Swartland'', Cinault produces varietal wines that are light in colour and low in tannin, often displaying bright cherries, earth and spice. Due to its heat tolerance, it is also important in Morocco and plays a key role in the red wines of Château Musar - Lebanon''s leading producer.', 'Cinsault / Cinsaut', 'It is a long established fact that a reader will be distracted by the readable content of a page when looking at its layout.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1302-autosave-v1', '', '', '2015-11-13 08:48:08', '2015-11-13 08:48:08', '', 1302, 'http://tests.shahum.net/1302-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
